{{zh-forms|s=驳|alt=駮,剝-"to refute; to transport by barge"}}

===Glyph origin===
{{Han etym}}
{{Han compound|馬|爻|c1=s|c2=p|t1=horse|ls=psc}}. The phonetic component adds part of the meaning if interpreted as "marks".

===Etymology===
{{etymon|zh|:inh|sit-pro:*prawk<id:piebald>|id=piebald}}
{{inh+|zh|sit-pro|*prawk|t=piebald}} ({{zh-ref|Schuessler, 2007}}, STEDT under PTB ''*bruk''); cognate with {{cog|my|ပြောက်|t=spotted, speckled}}, {{cog|kac|prúʔ}}, {{cog|mro|preu||of mixed colors}}. Another Chinese cognate may be {{och-l|斑}}.

{{och-l|豹|[[leopard]]}} is its exopassive derivative, literally meaning, “the spotted one”.

{{rfe|zh|The other senses are not obviously connected to the "variegated" sense, in particular, the "rebut" sense (which is the most prevalent sense in Sino-Xenic), though Schuessler makes no mention of them. Do these other senses derive from semantic extensions that originate in compound words which originally invoked the "variegated" sense? For example, {{och-l|駁船}} would be a "piebald boat" > "barge", and {{och-l|反駁}} would be something like "to go against the piebald (mixed)", perhaps evoking semantics which parallel {{ncog|en|go against the grain}}.}}

